<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,152,431]" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,464,153,179]" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">External morphology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[475,692,154,179]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Iophon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="42" pageNumber="503" phylum="Porifera" rank="subSpecies" species="situ" subSpecies="appearance">
<emphasis box="[475,692,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">In situ appearance</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[711,845,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 25. Dendrilla antarctica Topsent, 1905. BELUM.Mc2015.544. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376080/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">Figure 25A</figureCitation>
): Very bright luminous lemon yellow/neon yellow sponge with pronounced spiky conules. Form varies from simple encrusting specimens to ones with many lobes and branches. Specimens can be very large, some of ours were over 
<quantity box="[868,911,225,251]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="42" pageNumber="503" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
total diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,152,431]" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis box="[199,459,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">Preserved appearance.</emphasis>
Mass with clearly visible fibres within the tissue and protruding from surface conules. Colour is very dark maroon.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,152,431]" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,332,359]" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[315,444,332,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1235,1260]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[151,1436,481,1215]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 25. Dendrilla antarctica Topsent, 1905. BELUM.Mc2015.544. A. In situ appearance. B. Skeleton, scale bar 1000 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3376080/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="503">Figure 25B</figureCitation>
): Dendritic with fibres arising from a basal plate. These project from the surface, the ends forming the surface conules.
</paragraph>
